    "summary": "Roman gladiatorial games (ludi gladiatorii) originated as funeral rites in the 3rd century BC, with the first recorded event held in 264 BC when three pairs of gladiators fought at the funeral of Decimus Junius Brutus. Originally private affairs honoring the dead — the bloodshed was believed to appease the spirit of the deceased — they gradually evolved into public spectacles of immense political and social importance, eventually moving from the Forum to dedicated arenas.\n\nGladiators were typically slaves, prisoners of war, or condemned criminals, though some free men volunteered for the pay and fame. Training schools (ludi) run by entrepreneurs (lanistae) prepared fighters in specialized combat styles — secutor, retiarius, murmillo, Thracian — each with distinct weapons and armor. By the late Republic, ambitious politicians staged increasingly lavish munera (shows) as vote-buying tools; Julius Caesar staged 320 pairs of gladiators in silver armor. The games served complex social functions: they displayed the power of life and death, reinforced social hierarchy, and provided a shared spectacle binding Roman citizens across class lines. Slaves who survived multiple combats could earn their freedom (the rudis, a wooden sword). The games persisted until the 5th century AD.",
